collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description: This is important to remember that there will be continued gaps of both Academics and Social skills.
Evidence of lack of social skills due to Covid
Lots of pushback from students. Stamina is low.
School needs to be a priority.

Important to note that kids are not easily motivated. Teachers are going above an beyond to meet students for engagement and it is like stating, EXHAUSTING, as teachers to create, implement, and time from our teaching.
Teaching is about building relationships with students so that they do their best learning.
School and home working together is so important.

Developing an honest relationship with students is important. It is just as important to develop an honest relationship with administrators and school board members that make decisions for educating students, Modeling honesty is important so that students see honesty in action.
Building relationships with students is key to fostering learning.
Life long learners is so key!
Students need to learn how to communicate to have their needs met and to be a productive part of the world.
Inconsistency from place to place with the kiddos is important to remember. It's not just one place or person, it is everyone.
They struggle to do things on their own because it was either done for them, or they were not taught how to problem solve.
Students need to come to school ready to learn and more and more tihs is not happening.
Students that feel included seem to be able to learn better.
This is happening more and more every year.
Younger students have lived through COVID for most of their education and have been somewhat isolated in their learning and need to learn how to work together.

Teachers feel the pressure of families being more dependent on schools and are expecting the schools and teachers to meet their kids needs, not them. Basic gear feels expected for the school to supply. Not just winter gear, but school supplies as well. With our yearly budget, we have very little money to buy the basic needs, let alone the "extra". New teachers come in with zero supples. My budget for next year was to all the basics that you would expect to be in a classroom: pencils, paper, erasers, markers, construction paper, etc. That should be something that shouldn't have to come out of an individual teachers budget but maybe a school budget so teachers can get those extra tools and resources to provide more for the kiddos rather than basic needs that will not last a whole school year.
Students need to learn how to interact.
We are in desperate need of help teaching the SEL. Teacher's can't do it alone.
Students are fearful of getting sick and also fearful of active shooters coming to school.
COVID gave students a safe haven is a way. They felt protected from being sick and from school violence.
Evidence of putting more on the teachers
Students need to have activities that are engaging but also need to have some grit in doing activities that don't like to do.
Attendance is an issue for many students. How do we encourage better attendance and an overall importance for education?
There is a need for students to access more education both higher levels and for students to learn trades like plumbing, electrical work, carpentry and so on.
